INPUT MuRAT3D - Romania

This is an input file for the program Multi-Resolution Attenuation Tomography (MuRAT). It refers to the following area:
Romania

GENERAL FIELDS AND FIGURES

INPUTS in this section set the directory space where you want to work as well as the characteristics of the figure files you output. All these inputs are saved in the field of the Murat structure variable.
Start from the working directory. Best practice is to create a new folder where you create your workspace as MuRAT3D contains a folder with all the necessary functions. The code will save all your results inside a new folder he creates in the directory. In the example there are several directories containing the sac files (sac_*). The results of this example will be created in subfolders inside the Romania folder.
Murat.input.workingDirectory = './';
The folder containing waveform data is the next step. It MUST contain .sac files (beware of the difference between .sac and .SAC). For this example we will use data in the sac_MSH folder, so we input:
Murat.input.dataDirectory = './sac_Romania/*.sac';
Here you specify the name of the folder that will store results and figures - it will appear in your working directory:
Murat.input.label = 'Romania';
In MuRAT3D you can choose between a sequential (0) or parallelized (1) forward loop. In the parallelized case, select the number of workers. In this example, we are working with the parallelized code, which will use the function Murat_dataParallelized.
Murat.input.parallelized = 1;
Murat.input.workers = 8;
If set to 0 MuRAT3D will use Murat_data.
The next inputs can speed up the workflow, as they allow to only obtain parts of the figures. Setting them to zero avoids obtaining new figures that can clutter your desktop at each run.
Choose if figures related to data processing are to be created. If set to 1 it will output the test for stability of peak delay and Qc.
Murat.input.data = 1;
Choose if figures related to the velocity model are to be created. If set to 1 it will output the existing velocity model, rays, and Qc sensitivity kernels
Murat.input.geometry = 1;
Choose if figures related to the the inversion results are to be created. If set to 1 it will output the primary results.
Murat.input.inversion = 1;
Choose if figures related to the checkerboard test are to be created. If set to 1 it will output the input and output of the checkerboards for Q and Qc.
Murat.input.checkerboard = 1;
Choose if figures related to the spike test are to be created. If set to 1 it will output the input and output of the spike tests for Q and Qc.
Murat.input.spike = 1;

DATA DRIVEN CHOICES - WAVEFORMS

The in this section set all the variables required by data processing. This includes data choises, as setting the name of the variables in SAC and all the attributes that are needed for the three kinds of imaging.
As MuRAT3D is designed to work with sac files only, it is necessary to set the path to their peaking and zero time. This means that the files have to be peaked beforehand, and the origin time from the localization must be included in the haeder. The routines for loading the files have been mostly created by Zhigang Peng and co-workers and downloaded from their Introduction to SAC webpage.
So first set origin time, P-wave peaking and S-wave picking. If you don't have the origin time and S-wave times at hand you can mark it as unknown ([]). The P-wave picking is mandatory.
Murat.input.originTime = 'SAChdr.times.o';
Murat.input.PTime = 'SAChdr.times.t0';
Murat.input.STime = [];
You can check which field contains your picking by using fget_sac.m :
[times, seismogram, SAChdr] = fget_sac(name_of_sac_file.sac)
SAChdr is a structure that contains all the fields you saved in the SAC haeder. In this example the P-wave picking has been stored inside variable a. You always find these variables in the times subfield:
Afterwards, you need to choose the phase you are interested in - P- (2) or S- (3). In our case it is obviously P- as we have no S-wave picking.
Murat.input.POrS = 2;
The central frequency (Hz). You need to set it according to your spectrograms. General practice is to vary it across your spectra (see De Siena et al. 2016, EPSL) for absorption and scattering mapping or focus on a given frequency (De Siena et al. 2014, JGR) for direct-wave attenuation imaging.
Murat.input.centralFrequency = 6;
You can work with 1 vertical or horizontal (1), 2 horizontal (2) or three components(3). If using more than one component, the order MUST BE: WE, SN, Vertical or SN, WE, Vertical. In this example we work with the vertical component only.
Murat.input.components = 1;
To compute your envelopes you need to smooth them. The choise of smoothing parameters is empirical but you can get an idea of how to best pick the e.g. in Havskov et al. 2016, BSSA. It must always be > 2 and an integer. It will be divided by the central frequency as smoothing must be longer at lower frequencies.
Murat.input.smoothing = 8;

PEAK DELAY

Scattering (peak delay) measurements relies on measurements of coherent waves.
Peak delay is a standard measurements of forward scattering in regional scale-mapping since Takahashi et al. 2007, GJI. The tomographic developments of this work (same lead author, years 2008 and 2009) are important and we plan to include them for scattering imaging in the future. To do so, we will need to consider the order of the modified Bessel function of second kind, describing the von-Krmn type random medium with a new input as:
Murat.input.vonKarman = 0.5;
Here, we approach the problem by simply adding a ray-tracing strategy to the system, assuming that the sensitivity follows the seismic ray Also we bring it to 3D and apply it to P-waves with the approach described in De Siena et al. 2016, EPSL.
To do so we need to set a minimum peak delay (s) considering scattering in the area and frequency. If using P wave this is important, as they can be sometimes more energetic than S-waves, biasing our measurements, but this is not the case for Romania.
Murat.input.minimumPeakDelay = 0.1;
Obviusly we also need to set the maximum peack-delay (s) t), not to peak anomalous surface waves - see Takahashi et al. 2007, GJI.
Murat.input.maximumPeakDelay = 10;

DIRECT WAVE ATTENUATION

Total attenuation (inverse Q) measurements also relies on measurements of coherent waves.
Total attenuation with the coda-normalization method is today astandard in volcano tomography. First used by Del Pezzo et al. 2006, PEPI at Mount Vesuvius, it has been the core of MuRAT1.0, the seminal code published in De Siena et al. 2014, JVGR. The method has been applied so far to Campi Flegrei (De Siena et al. 2010, JGR; De Siena et al. 2017, Scientific Reports), Mount St Helens (De Siena et al. 2014, JGR), Deception Island (Prudencio et al. 2015); Tenerife (Prudencio et al. 2015) and Long Valley (Prudencio & Manga, 2020). There are three more volcanoes where the application is undergoing.
The method relies on the measurements of both direct and coda wave energy - this second will come in handy for coda attenuation imaging. Therefore we need to set the spectral energy decay of the coda wavefield, either surface (0.5) or body waves (1)
Murat.input.spectralDecay = 0.5;
Then we set the length of the window used to measure noise and direct wave intensity, trying to smooth radiation pattern effects. Discussions on the topic can be found in De Siena et al. 2009, PEPI and De Siena et al. 2010, JGR, but the choise is as usual dependent on data.
Murat.input.bodyWindow = 1;
We also need the start of the window used to measure noise before the origin time of the recording. As the window used to easure noise energy is relatively small we generally have no prblems, except if other waveforms arrive before (e.g., drunbeats).
Murat.input.startNoise = 5;
The coda-to-noise energy ratio is used as a weight for the inversion. Here you set the minimum accepted energy ratio.
Murat.input.tresholdNoise = 3;

CODA ATTENUATION

Coda attenuation (inverse Qc) is measured from the decay of the coda with laps time from the origin time of the earthquake.
Qc is a well know parameter for assesing tectonic structures (Sato et al. 2012, Springer). In recent years it has been used as an imaging attribute at the regional (Calvet et al. 2013, Tectonophysics; Borleanu et al. 2017, Tectonophysics), fault (Napolitano et al. 2020; Sketsiou et al. 2020, PEPI) and, especially, volcanic scales (Prudencio et al. 2013a, GJI; Prudencio et al. 2013b GJI; De Siena et al. 2016, EPSL; De Siena et al. 2017, GRL; Gabrielli et al. 2020, GJI).
In MuRAT3D, we use the full 3D computational kernels devised by Del Pezzo et al. 2018, Geosciences in the inversion approach proposed first by De Siena et al. 2017, GRL. These kernels are computed for a given starting time of the coda window:
Murat.input.startLapseTime = 30;
and coda window length:
Murat.input.codaWindow = 30;
The true lapse time at which we calculate the kernels is half of the window. The window is also used (after normalizing for its length) in the coda normalization method. As these kernels are computational intensive and require a full matrix of nodes to avoid singularities, we also use a computational treshold to reduce the computational time:
Murat.input.kernelTreshold = 2;
This number divides the input grid so the higher it is the denser is the node spacing. A figure will also output the kernel in this grid.
MuRAT3D implements both a linearised (0) and a non-linear (1) approach:
Murat.input.nonLinear = 0;
The linearised approach is the standard proposed first by Aki (e.g., Havskov et al. 2016, BSSA) to best fit Qc after taking the logarithm of the enrgy:
if Murat.input.nonLinear == 0
The uncertainties can be derived from the simple minimum R-squared for Qc fitting, which will also play as a weight in the final inversion. Regardless, it is advisable to set a minimum treshold near to zero, so that only positive defied fit are accepted. The maxm possibl R-square is one (perfect fit) so the choise is again dependent on the qulity of the data. While here we use:
Murat.input.fitTresholdLinear = 0.1;
it is advisable to use a higher number in real pplication, especially for arrays that cover well the area.
A second approach is to model energy data measured on smaller windows and minimize the difference between data and model with a 1D grid search algorithm (Napolitano et al. 2020):
elseif Murat.input.nonLinear == 1
To do so it is necessary to set the maximum allowed residual between observed and computed energies, that work in analogy to the linearised case:
Murat.input.fitTresholdNonLinear= 2;
Again, this must be set depending on your data and, importantly, unity of measurement.
As with this method we compute energy on smaller coda windows, we need to divide our original time window (which is 15 s for this example) into a number N of smaller windows - in this case 5 windows:
Murat.input.fitNumberWindows = 5;
of length of 3 seconds:
Murat.input.fitLengthWindows = 3;
As this is a grid search, we need to define the parameter space, thus the minimum inverse Qc:
Murat.input.minimumQcGrid = 0;
and maximum inverse Qc allowed:
Murat.input.maximumQcGrid = 0.01;
toghether with the amount of Qc in the interval:
Murat.input.totalQcNumber = 1001;%E
end
In this example we search the best Qc between 1001 equally-spaced Qc values ranging between 0 and 0.01.

GEOMETRY AND VELOCITY

This section sets the details of the inversion grid. In MuRAT3D the coordinates of the model are in lat/lon and get then converted in km. The vertical is in altitude above sea level, starting from the top point.
The characteristics of the model are:
  1. the origin must be put at least one cell before the westernmost and southernmost earthquakes/station for increasing latitudes and longitudes;
  2. the end point must be put at least one cell after the easternmost and northermost earthquakes/station for increasing latitudes and longitudes;
  3. if the origin is given in UTM then convert to degrees: use utm2deg within the utilities, created by Gabriel Ruiz Martinez - see the MHS example.
Murat.input.origin = [43 20 0];
Murat.input.end = [48 29 -50000];
Then you need to set the number of nodes in the three directions. This is obviously dependent on the scale of your area. You will be playing alot with this to test your resolution.
Murat.input.gridLat = 5;
Murat.input.gridLong = 9;
Murat.input.gridZ = 6;
With this version of the code you are always using an underlying velocity model. You can either use a 1D (0) or a 3D (1) velocity model:
Murat.input.availableVelocity = 0;
Here we have no 3D model so we useh iasp91.txt, the standard IASPEI velocity model and expand it to a false 3D. However, a standard crustal model is generally available everywhere on the Earth, so use that - but change it to the same format as the file provided, first column is depth, second is distance from the centre of the Earth, then third and fourth are P- and S-wave velocity.
Murat.input.namev = 'iasp91.txt';
Even if we set the velocity model we still need the average crustal velocities for some petty calculations, particularly the Vp/Vs ratio (this is required if we use P-wave to get the envelope peak delays) and if you have no info of origin time:
Murat.input.averageVelocityP = 6;
Murat.input.averageVelocityS = 3;
At last, the code still has a deprecated option in case the location of the earthquake is not set in the SAC files. This is set to 1 only if you want to import external files with locations of events and stations:
Murat.input.importLocation = 0;
This is not the case here - see the MSH input for an example.

RESULTS - INCLUDES INVERSION, TESTING AND PLOTTING

The last section has inputs necessary to test yourQc and Q map - as peak delay only regionalizes. Most of these code rely on the regtools Matlab suite from Per Christian Hansen. As you need to select the damping you can choose (1) to output the L curves between residual and norm length (Aster et al. 2013) or not (0). In this case you do:
Murat.input.lCurve = 1;
However, it is likely that you will test many different dampi parameters and want to avoid seeing the same figure again, so you can just declare the damping for Qc and Q:
if Murat.input.lCurve == 0
Murat.input.lCurveQc = 0.15;
Murat.input.lCurveQ = 0.03;
end
Also, if you want to testing you results you need to create a checkerboard. The size of the checks can be twice (2) or four times (4) node spacing.
Murat.input.sizeCheck = 2;
each cell having alternating values of attenuation:
Murat.input.highCheck = 0.02;
Murat.input.lowCheck = 0.001;
A great reference for the best sort of testing is Rawlinson & Spakman, 2016. In it you find that spikes can be more useful than chekerboards so in MuRAT3D you set the origin ad end locations of the spike as:
Murat.input.spikeLocationOrigin = [44 23 -10000];
Murat.input.spikeLocationEnd = [46 25 -30000];
while its value is:
Murat.input.spikeValue = 0.02;
The last inputs are:
  • your preferred figure format - 'jpeg' (fast) or 'tiff' (for publication):
Murat.input.format = 'jpeg';
  • figure visibility during computation - pick on if you want to see them all in real time, but off is he best choice to avoid cluttering your scree:
Murat.input.visibility = 'on';
  • the sections where you will slice your plots. MuRAT3D now saves everything in Paraview format (.VTK) but some checks in Matlab can be useful. You will see all of your figures on three sections cutting the models WE (degrees), SN (degrees), and horizontally (meters or km) at:
Murat.input.sections = [45 25 -10000];
  • finally, choose big are markers for stations and events in all your figures:
Murat.input.sizeMarker = 60;
